<p class="content__abstract">
  This article introduces CSS, the language used to style web pages. Read it to learn how to apply CSS rules to your website.
</p>

<p>Your website has some content, but it‚Äôs using the default styling that comes with your browser. You can override these defaults with CSS. CSS stands for Cascading Style Sheets, so called because later rules override earlier ones, in a cascade. As an example, the colour of h1 text with the following stylesheet will be green, because green is the last instruction.</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-css" data-lang="css">  <span class="nt">h1</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">color</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="no">blue</span><span class="p">;</span>
    <span class="nl">color</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="no">green</span><span class="p">;</span>
  <span class="p">}</span></code></pre></figure>

<h2 id="view-the-browsers-default-styles">View the browser‚Äôs default styles</h2>

<p>Let‚Äôs view what our styles looks like currently. In the browser, right mouse and click on <strong>Inspect</strong>.</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/inspect.png" alt="" /></p>

<p>The styles panel on the right shows me that the default styles for the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code> HTML tag are that the font size is 2em (as in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Em_(typography)">em-dash</a>) and the font weight is bold:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-css" data-lang="css">  <span class="nt">h1</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">font-size</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="m">2em</span><span class="p">;</span>
    <span class="nl">font-weight</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">bold</span><span class="p">;</span>
  <span class="p">}</span></code></pre></figure>

<blockquote>
  <p><span class="content__learn-more">The browser‚Äôs inspector</span></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Notice too that raw HTML is also displayed in the Inspect panel, in the Elements tab, on Chrome (other browsers may be a little different, but essentially do the same thing). Compare the HTML here with the HTML in your file. It‚Äôs the same, give or take some whitespace. The Inspector is a good place to go to troubleshoot and debug your code when problems arise.</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>

<h2 id="add-css-to-override-the-default-style">Add CSS to override the default style</h2>

<p>Open the file called <code class="highlighter-rouge">main.scss</code> in the css folder:</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/main-css.png" alt="" /></p>

<p>Add the following CSS to this file and save:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-css" data-lang="css">  <span class="nt">h1</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">color</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="no">red</span><span class="p">;</span>
  <span class="p">}</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>So the entire file looks like this:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-css" data-lang="css">  <span class="nt">---</span>
  <span class="nt">---</span>

  <span class="o">//</span> <span class="nt">You</span> <span class="nt">will</span> <span class="nt">put</span> <span class="nt">CSS</span> <span class="nt">style</span> <span class="nt">information</span> <span class="nt">here</span><span class="o">.</span>

  <span class="nt">h1</span> <span class="p">{</span>
    <span class="nl">color</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="no">red</span><span class="p">;</span>
  <span class="p">}</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Refresh the browser page. You expect the colour of the heading to go red, right? But it‚Äôs not changed. What has gone wrong? Let‚Äôs debug the problem.</p>

<h2 id="debug-the-problem">Debug the problem</h2>

<p>First, look in your Inspector, in the HTML Elements panel. Is the HTML tag indeed <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code>? Yes, that is correct. The word ‚ÄúPortfolio‚Äù is surrounded by <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code> tags:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;h1&gt;</span>
    Portfolio
    <span class="nt">&lt;span</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"header__subtitle"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>Incredible stories, published with love<span class="nt">&lt;/span&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;/h1&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Now look at the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code> style definition in the Inspector. Does the <code class="highlighter-rouge">color: red</code> instruction appear? No. So the code we wrote isn‚Äôt getting referenced. The solution is to add a reference to the CSS file so that the browser knows to run it when it interprets the HTML file.</p>

<p>In the <code class="highlighter-rouge">portfolio.html</code> file, add the following line between the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;head&gt;</code> tags and save:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;link</span> <span class="na">rel=</span><span class="s">"stylesheet"</span> <span class="na">href=</span><span class="s">"/css/main.css"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Your file now looks like this:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="cp">&lt;!doctype html&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;html&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;head&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;link</span> <span class="na">rel=</span><span class="s">"stylesheet"</span> <span class="na">href=</span><span class="s">"/css/main.css"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;/head&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;body&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;div</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"header__background"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;h1&gt;</span>
          Portfolio
          <span class="nt">&lt;span</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"header__subtitle"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>Incredible stories, published with love<span class="nt">&lt;/span&gt;</span>
        <span class="nt">&lt;/h1&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;/div&gt;</span>
      <span class="nt">&lt;section</span> <span class="na">class=</span><span class="s">"container__portfolio"</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span>
        Book list goes here
      <span class="nt">&lt;/section&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;/body&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;/html&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Refresh your browser and now you‚Äôll see the changes applied:</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/css-red.png" alt="" /></p>

<h2 id="use-the-inspector-to-make-temporary-edits">Use the inspector to make temporary edits</h2>

<p>You can temporarily make changes in the Inspector to see how they‚Äôd look on the page. Have a go: make the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;h1&gt;</code> text go blue.</p>

<p><img src="assets/images/css-blue.gif" alt="" /></p>

<h2 id="what-youve-learned">What you‚Äôve learned</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Browsers have default styling, but it‚Äôs not pretty</li>
  <li>We use CSS to override these default styles, and add new ones</li>
  <li>The HTML page needs to know where its CSS stylesheet is, via a link in the <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;head&gt;</code> of the HTML file</li>
  <li>The inspector is a handy tool for debugging and trying out changes to the CSS.</li>
  <li>CSS rules are applied in a cascade, hence the name. Later styles override earlier ones.</li>
</ul>

